coins.reversedesign: The European Council decided, on 7 June 2005, that the common side of all the coin denominations should be updated to reflect the enlargement of the EU in 2004. The new designs have maps that represent Europe as a geographical whole. They are being introduced progressively, starting with the coins issued by the new entrants to the euro area from 2007 onwards. Some other euro-area Member States also started to apply them in 2007, and they became mandatory for all new coin production from 2008.

coins.obversedesign: Modern portrait of Marianne, the personification of the French Republic
coins.subject: In France, a competition was organised in 1996-1997 to choose the design of the national sides of the euro coins. A panel, chaired by the Minister for Economic and Financial Affairs and made up of experts in numismatics, artists, members of parliament, one former member of the European Commission (Christine Scrivener), the French Mint Director Emmanuel Constans, the General Engraver Pierre Rodier, actress Irène Jacob and members of professional bodies, chose the winning designs from over 1 200 entries received from 97 participants.

coins.subject: The Brandenburg Gate, a symbol of the division of Germany and its subsequent unification, is the motif used on these coins. The perspective of the design, by Reinhard Heinsdorff, emphasises the opening of the gate, stressing the unification of Germany and Europe.

coins.reversedesign: The European Council decided, on 7 June 2005, that the common side of all the coin denominations should be updated to reflect the enlargement of the EU in 2004. The new designs have maps that represent Europe as a geographical whole. They are being introduced progressively, starting with the coins issued by the new entrants to the euro area from 2007 onwards. Some other euro-area Member States also started to apply them in 2007, and they became mandatory for all new coin production from 2008.
